\section{Introduction}

It is unlikely that observations will ever allow us to pin down the fundamental theory responsible for inflation~\cite{Guth:1980zm, Linde:1981mu, Albrecht:1982wi, Starobinsky:1980te, Mukhanov:1981xt}. Instead, we might have to conform ourselves with gaining general insights into the origin of cosmological perturbations with the help of the effective field theory (EFT) approach to inflation~\cite{Cheung:2007st}. This consists of a powerful and model independent framework to study the evolution of curvature perturbations ${\mathcal R}$ during inflation, valid at energies around the Hubble expansion rate $H$. With the help of simple symmetry arguments, it is possible to derive the most general class of Lagrangians governing the dynamics of fluctuations in a Friedman-Robertson-Walker (FRW) background, in the form a Goldstone boson field $\pi = - {\mathcal R} / H$, and given by an operator expansion with non-linearly related coefficients parametrizing physics beyond the canonical single-field slow-roll paradigm. These coefficients are determined by the putative ultraviolet complete theory underlying inflation, among which the sound speed $c_s$ plays a prominent role. To quadratic order, the Lagrangian is given by~\cite{Cheung:2007st}

where $M_{\rm Pl}$ is the reduced Planck mass and $a$ is the scale factor. The sound speed $c_s$ also defines the strength of various self-interactions appearing at cubic and quartic orders, leading to sizable deviations from Gaussianity provided that $c_s^2 \ll 1$~\cite{Chen:2006nt, Senatore:2009gt}. Moreover, it has been recently conjectured~\cite{Baumann:2015nta} that every non-trivial parameter of the EFT expansion must be proportional to $(c_s^{-2} - 1)$. In that case, single field slow-roll inflation would be the only single field theory compatible with the limit $c_s \to 1$.  

Current observational constraints on primordial non-Gaussianity give $c_s \geq 0.024$ (95\%CL)~\cite{Ade:2015ava}. Future measurements will allow us to further constrain the coefficients of the EFT Lagrangian, narrowing down the class of fundamental theories that can host inflation together with the standard model of particle physics. It is therefore important to understand the details on how do fundamental theories map into the EFT operator expansion. Because observations favor primordial perturbations generated by a single scalar degree of freedom~\cite{Ade:2015ava}, we expect that any theory pretending to embed inflation must allow for a single field description valid at energies around $H$. This should be particularly true for theories that predict a large number of degrees of freedom, such as supergravity and string theory.

Given that supergravity theories are characterized by having several scalar fields, it is conceivable that the inflationary path experienced bends. Regardless of how massive are the fields orthogonal to the inflationary trajectory, these bends affect the EFT describing the evolution of the Goldston boson mode $\pi$~\cite{Tolley:2009fg, Achucarro:2010da}. Indeed, it is now well understood that each time a bend occurs during inflation, the local angular velocity $\Omega$ that describes the bend reduces the value of the sound speed $c_s$.  In the particular case of two-field models, one has~\cite{Achucarro:2010da, Achucarro:2012sm, Achucarro:2012yr}

