\section{Discusion}

Let us now analyze the content of eq.~(\ref{main-result-full}). To start with, notice that the smallest attainable value of the lhs of (\ref{main-result-full}) is given by $- 3/4$. This means that, when the inflationary trajectory is subjected to strong bends, it is possible to have $M^2 > 0$ simultaneously with a large and negative value of $\eta_V$. Next, the rhs of eq.~(\ref{main-result-full}) may acquire any desired value, depending on the specific K\"ahler potential of the supergravity at hand. Nevertheless, we expect this value to be of order $1$. First of all, the natural value of the curvature $\mathbb{R}(f)$ at the rhs is given by $\mathbb{R}(f) \simeq \mathcal O (1)$. For instance, canonical models are characterized by $\mathbb{R}(f)  = 0$ whereas single-chiral-field no-scale models satisfy $\mathbb{R}(f) = 2/3$. In second place, there are two classes of models of supergravity inflation depending on the value of $\gamma = H^2 / m_{3/2}^2$. On the one hand, we expect the value of $H$ during inflation to be of order $10^{14}$GeV or smaller, but not too much smaller (in order to have a tensor to scalar ratio $r \lesssim 0.1$). On the other hand, we expect the value of $m_{3/2}$ at the end of inflation to be of order $1$TeV or larger, but not too much larger (in order to have a soft supersymmetry breaking scale close to the electroweak symmetry breaking scale). Hence, in models where $m_{3/2}$ did not evolve significantly during inflation, one expects $\gamma \gtrsim 1$, implying that the rhs of eq.~(\ref{main-result-full}) must be of order $1$. It is possible to conceive models where $\gamma \ll 1$, potentially implying that the rhs of eq.~(\ref{main-result-full}) could be much larger than $1$. However, in such models the combination $2/3  -  \mathbb{R}(f)$ typically remains suppressed, implying that the rhs eq.~(\ref{main-result-full}) stays of order 1. Prototype examples of such models are large volume scenarios~\cite{Conlon:2008cj}, where one finds that $2/3  -  \mathbb{R}(f) \sim \gamma$~\footnote{Bare in mind, however, that these models require at least two chiral fields.}. 

